off the teeth and a
little sickly smile,

00:49:59.720 --> 00:50:02.610
it made you feel just the way
those broken eggs must feel

00:50:02.610 --> 00:50:05.640
against your seat, as queer
and awful as that time

00:50:05.640 --> 00:50:07.820
in the white PK suit."

00:50:07.820 --> 00:50:10.740
He's also dramatizing how
personal our relation to film

00:50:10.740 --> 00:50:11.910
can be.

00:50:11.910 --> 00:50:13.639
"When it ran down out
of the pants' legs,

00:50:13.639 --> 00:50:15.430
and showed all over
your stockings, and you

00:50:15.430 --> 00:50:18.390
had to walk home that way
with everyone looking.

00:50:18.390 --> 00:50:20.700
And Rufus's father nearly
tore his head off laughing,

00:50:20.700 --> 00:50:22.180
and so did everybody else.

00:50:22.180 --> 00:50:25.140
But Rufus was sorry for
Charlie, having so recently

00:50:25.140 --> 00:50:27.550
been in a similar predicament.

00:50:27.550 --> 00:50:30.885
But the contagion of laughter
was too much for him,

00:50:30.885 --> 00:50:31.760
and he laughed, too."

00:50:31.760 --> 00:50:33.970
And the passage
goes on to describe

00:50:33.970 --> 00:50:37.360
the intimacy and the
complexity of the relations

00:50:37.360 --> 00:50:40.140
between audiences
in 1915 and one

00:50:40.140 --> 00:50:42.820
of the iconic figures
of the movies.

00:50:42.820 --> 00:50:46.890
In this idea, that
Charlie mobilizes

00:50:46.890 --> 00:50:49.660
this anarchic,
liberating laughter,

00:50:49.660 --> 00:50:53.930
and mobilizes this
father-son relationship.

00:50:53.930 --> 00:50:56.720
In that idea we
recapture something

00:50:56.720 --> 00:50:59.090
of what I mean by
the notion that

00:50:59.090 --> 00:51:01.680
film was an embedded
social experience,

00:51:01.680 --> 00:51:03.400
an embedded social form.

00:51:03.400 --> 00:51:05.550
I'll see you tonight.

